    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-05T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-05T11:00:00-05:00" n="285"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/283</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé d’Affaires in China</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MJVA1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-06T00:00:00+08:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">August 6, 1914, 12 midnight</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>The Chinese Government is addressing to the Department of State a request in the
                    sense outlined in my telegram of August 3, 11 p.m. It is also simultaneously
                    requesting the Japanese Government to cooperate with ours in this matter. It is
                    planned that the President of China will to-morrow address his request to the
                    President directly.</p>
                <p>I beg to request that as the Diplomatic Body has not been willing to take up the
                    question of the neutralization of the treaty ports, referred to in my telegram
                    of August 3, 5 p.m., it might be advisable to suggest to the belligerents that,
                    even though failing a complete <pb facs="0477" n="163" xml:id="pg_163"/>
                    exclusion of the Far East from the area of hostilities, they instruct their
                    representatives to maintain the principle of neutrality throughout their
                    jurisdiction in China. It is earnestly hoped that the attitude of the German
                    Government in this matter may be made known to the Legation for communication to
                    the Chinese Government as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MJVA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
